<subSubSection type="etymology">
<paragraph pageNumber="545">
Etymology Gr 
<taxonomicName LSID-HNS="urn:lsid:biosci.ohio-state.edu:osuc_concepts:33676" class="Insecta" family="Formicidae" genus="Pheidole" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName="Pheidole colobopsis Mann" lsidName-HNS="Pheidole colobopsis Mann" order="Hymenoptera" pageNumber="545" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="colobopsis">colobopsis</taxonomicName>
, docked, clipped, shortened, with reference to the truncated head of the major.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection type="diagnosis">
<paragraph pageNumber="545">
Diagnosis A typical member of the 
<taxonomicName LSID-HNS="urn:lsid:biosci.ohio-state.edu:osuc_concepts:33822" class="Insecta" family="Formicidae" genus="Pheidole" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName="Pheidole lamia Wheeler" lsidName-HNS="Pheidole lamia Wheeler" order="Hymenoptera" pageNumber="545" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="lamia">lamia</taxonomicName>
group: the major has a phragmotic head, with the anterior portion incorporating the clypeus and mandibles flattened (truncated), and deep antennal scrobes. This species is easily distinguished from the other members of the 
<taxonomicName LSID-HNS="urn:lsid:biosci.ohio-state.edu:osuc_concepts:33822" class="Insecta" family="Formicidae" genus="Pheidole" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName="Pheidole lamia Wheeler" lsidName-HNS="Pheidole lamia Wheeler" order="Hymenoptera" pageNumber="545" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="lamia">lamia</taxonomicName>
group (
<taxonomicName LSID-HNS="urn:lsid:biosci.ohio-state.edu:osuc_concepts:33822" class="Insecta" family="Formicidae" genus="Pheidole" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName="Pheidole lamia Wheeler" lsidName-HNS="Pheidole lamia Wheeler" order="Hymenoptera" pageNumber="545" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="lamia">lamia</taxonomicName>
, 
<taxonomicName LSID-HNS="urn:lsid:biosci.ohio-state.edu:osuc_concepts:181964" class="Insecta" family="Formicidae" genus="Pheidole" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName="Pheidole pelor Wilson" lsidName-HNS="Pheidole pelor Wilson" order="Hymenoptera" pageNumber="545" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="pelor">pelor</taxonomicName>
, 
<taxonomicName LSID-HNS="urn:lsid:biosci.ohio-state.edu:osuc_concepts:181965" class="Insecta" family="Formicidae" genus="Pheidole" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName="Pheidole truncula Wilson" lsidName-HNS="Pheidole truncula Wilson" order="Hymenoptera" pageNumber="545" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="truncula">truncula</taxonomicName>
) by the shorter head of the major and the pattern of carinulae on its head: limited to dense longitudinal rows on the frontal lobes and frontal triangle and transverse rows on the lateral wings of the clypeus. Other differences in body form and sculpturing are as illustrated. The queen is also phragmotic.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection type="description">
<paragraph pageNumber="545">Measurements (mm) Major (Rio Porce, Colombia): HW 1.08, HL 1.20, SL 0.54, EL 0.14, PW 0.60. Minor (Rio Porce, Colombia): HW 0.52, HL 0.54, SL 0.52, EL 0.06, PW 0.32.</paragraph>
<paragraph pageNumber="545">color Major: mostly light reddish brown; appendages, the truncated front of the head, and a narrow horizontal strip posterior to the eyes dark yellow.</paragraph>
<paragraph pageNumber="545">Minor: body and scapes medium reddish brown, other appendages yellowish brown.</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection type="distribution">
<paragraph pageNumber="545">Range Known only from series collected in Rondonia, Brazil, Rio Porce, Colombia, and Cuzco Amazonico, Madre de Dios, Peru.</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection type="biology_ecology">
<paragraph pageNumber="545">biology The Peruvian colony was collected in clay soil at the base of a tree in terra firme rainforest. The nest was 12 cm deep and contained a single queen, five majors, and about 200 minors. The majors and minors in this series are a nearly uniform dark yellow to amber color.</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
